{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604359"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:52:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15822"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15822"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.13,0.07,0.53,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8513"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71470"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8513","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8513"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15822"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56979"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"8611"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20451"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71470","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71470"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring week three of embryological development, the primitive heart tube forms from the fusion of paired endocardial tubes. The heart tube contains five distinct regions arranged in sequence from cranial to caudal end.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct cranial-to-caudal arrangement of regions in the primitive heart tube?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Truncus arteriosus, primitive ventricle, bulbus cordis, primitive atrium, sinus venosus","Primitive atrium, sinus venosus, primitive ventricle, bulbus cordis, truncus arteriosus","Sinus venosus, primitive ventricle, primitive atrium, bulbus cordis, truncus arteriosus","Truncus arteriosus, bulbus cordis, primitive ventricle, primitive atrium, sinus venosus","Sinus venosus, primitive atrium, primitive ventricle, bulbus cordis, truncus arteriosus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primitive heart tube forms during the third week of development and consists of five distinct regions arranged in a specific cranial-to-caudal sequence. From cranial to caudal end, these regions are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETruncus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E - develops into the ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBulbus cordis\u003C/strong\u003E - forms most of the right ventricle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimitive ventricle\u003C/strong\u003E - develops into the left ventricle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimitive atrium\u003C/strong\u003E - gives rise to both atrial chambers\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinus venosus\u003C/strong\u003E - contributes to the right atrium and coronary sinus\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis arrangement is present before cardiac looping begins around day 23. During looping, the heart tube bends rightward to establish the basic spatial relationships between the future cardiac chambers.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The primitive heart tube forms from the fusion of paired endocardial tubes during week three of development.","The primitive heart tube has five distinct regions arranged in a specific cranial-to-caudal sequence.","The regions of the heart tube develop into specific adult cardiac structures."],"references":["Sadler TW. Langman\u0027s Medical Embryology: Wolters Kluwer; 2015."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56979"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15822"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56979"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T18:13:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T18:14:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8513"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71470"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiovascular","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"202